INSERT INTO `t_about` VALUES (29, '1', '1', '1', '<pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">In 2007, Amazon released the first generation of e-reader Kindle, which is equipped with a 6-inch 4th-order electronic paper ink screen.With the popularity of the Kindle, e-paper is truly familiar to consumers.\nElectronic Paper (ePaper) is a display technology that mimics the visual perception of printing and writing on paper.\n\n\nE-paper enthusiasts gathering organized by netizen “Tuanzi”\nUnlike ordinary flat panel displays that display images with illuminating light, electronic papers use electrophoresis display (EPD) as a display panel. They rely on reflected ambient light to display images, which are more comfortable to read and can display images.It is still clearly visible under direct sunlight, and has a wide viewing angle, theoretically up to 180 degrees.\nE-paper is flexible and low-power, and is widely used in reading and writing, mobile wear, electronic shelf labels, electronic signage, architecture and design.\n\n\nHowever, looking back on the past, the development of electronic paper has also encountered many crises.From the birth of the 1960s to the real large-scale application at the beginning of this century, e-paper has experienced many difficulties and obstacles.\nIn the era of LCD technology, how did e-paper break through?\nElectronic paper or LCD screen? Panasonic’s hesitation\nThe first electronic paper in history was not from E Ink, but a famous Japanese electrical appliance company, Panasonic.\n\n\nPanasonic\nIn 1968, the Radio Corporation of America (RCA) published the theory that “displays can be made using liquid crystal materials.” This theory later became the basis for the development of liquid crystal panels.\nAt the time, 太田勋夫, who developed the electronic photo display liquid, was shocked when he heard the news. He immediately started researching it. After the research, he boldly came to the conclusion that electrophoresis technology is more promising than liquid crystal technology in display applications.\n太田勋夫 began to develop electrophoretic electronic paper. In 1969, he applied for several patents related to electrophoresis technology.\nIn the 1970s, Panasonic began to market its products.At the same time, another electronic paper technology “Gyricon” was born in 1970. It was developed by the famous Xerox Palo Alto Research Center, where the mouse, laser printer, graphical user interface and page description language Interpress were born.Major inventions that affect the historical process of the 20th century.\n\n\nPalo Alto Research Center\nHowever, the good times did not last long. In 1976, Panasonic suddenly chose to stop developing electronic paper and turned to the LCD screen field.\nIt may be because the product repair rate at that time was extremely high, and it may be due to the envy of the Sharp LCD display calculator.\n\n\nThe earliest LCD calculator Sharp EL-8020\nFrom the perspective of interests, Panasonic’s choice may be right. After several decades, LCD monitors have brought huge gains to Panasonic.\nHowever, the development of electronic paper has thus stagnate, and Xerox’s Gyricon has only lived in the laboratory.\nWill e-paper be going to fail?\nThe development of electronic paper technology, the birth of E Ink\nIt was not until the 1990s that after 20 years of decadence, electronic paper finally ushered in spring.\nIn 1995, in the MIT Media Lab, Professor Neil Gershenfeld, physicist Joseph Jacobson, mathematics student Barrett Comiskey, and mechanical engineering student JD Albert co-created E Ink.\nElectrophoretic ink technology is commonly known as electronic ink.The electronic ink is coated on a layer of plastic film, and then attached to a thin film transistor (TFT) circuit, and controlled by a driver IC to form a pixel pattern to create an electronic paper display (EPD).\n\n\nElectrophoretic electronic ink technology\nThey then applied for a patent and in 1997 they teamed up to create the E Ink company.\nSince then, electronic paper has begun to enter the public’s field of vision.\nThe road to commercialization of electronic paper, E Ink dominates the field of electronic paper\nThrough the wave of e-ink technology, in May 1999, E Ink launched an outdoor e-paper called Immedia for advertising.\nHowever, what really caused a sensation was the “e-newspaper” conceptual model launched by IBM in the same year.\n\n\nIBM e-newspaper conceptual model\nIn 1999, at the largest newspaper exhibition in the United States, IBM demonstrated an “e-newspaper” that could read text and image information through an electronic display layer, attracting attention from the newspaper publishing industry around the world.The New York Times and The Washington Post spoke highly of the “e-newspaper”, claiming that this e-reading has revolutionary significance, and BusinessWeek also awarded the annual IDEA American Industrial Design Award to the “Electronic Newspaper.”In recognition of its cross-age value in terms of printing cost savings and news timeliness.\n\n\nIDEA American Industrial Design Excellence Award\nRobert Steinbugler, who is the chief designer of IBM and the head of the “electronic newspaper” project, proudly said: “People will be able to see the part of the newspaper that they are most interested in anytime and anywhere, and the electronic newspaper will be spread all over the world.”\nHowever, at that time, the development of the network had not reached the level that could support this idea. The “electronic newspaper” eventually became the fantasy of IBM.However, it seems now that the concept of customized information flow contained in the “electronic newspaper” happens to be the focus of competition among major Internet giants in more than a decade.\nIBM’s “failure” did not delay the development of e-paper. From 00 to 2002, new technologies such as curled e-paper and color e-paper were introduced.\nIn 2004, the road to commercialization of electronic paper finally ushered in a historic breakthrough, and Sony once again became a pioneer in the industry.\n\n\nSony LIBRle\nThe world’s first commercially available electronic paper “LIBRIe”, powered by Eink and Philips, was produced by Sony.The LIBRIe measures 190×126×13mm and weighs only 190g. It only needs 4 batteries and 7 batteries to browse 10,000 pages. The careful Sony also provides users with 4 kinds of contrast adjustment and recording functions also joined by Sony to LIBRIe.\nThe launch of the electronic paper of 40,000 yen has attracted worldwide attention and, more importantly, it has led to new developments in the electronic paper industry.\n\n\nElectronic companies around the world are rushing to develop e-paper products, and they are aware of the huge potential of the e-paper market.\nIn 2005, Seiko released the first electronic ink watch called Spectrum SVRD001, which looks like a crafted bracelet that uses the softness of electronic paper to make it extremely thin and low-power design effect.\n\n\nSpectrum SVRD001 Watch\nIn 2007, Amazon released the first generation of e-reader Kindle. What Amazon didn’t expect was that this e-ink screen product was sold out for five hours after it was sold. Amazon will not be able to resume supply until several months later。\n\n\nKindle becomes the iconic product of electronic ink screen\nOn June 1, 2009, E Ink announced that it will be acquired by its major business partner Yuan Tai for more than US$400 million, which has accelerated the development of electronic paper technology.And, by 2012, E Ink acquired SiPix, one of only a few competitors.\n\n\nBy this time, most of the electronic paper products used E Ink’s technology.With about 90% of the electronic paper market share, E Ink finally established the “electronic paper” empire.\nThe impact of the IPAD? Electronic paper goes its own way\nE Ink looks to the farther future, but this road will not be smooth.\nIn the early morning of January 28th, 2010, Steve Jobs, who was slightly gaunt, stood on the podium of the Yerba Buena Art Center in San Francisco: “Apple will bring you a revolutionary new product… its size is between IPHONE and MACBOOK.In the meantime, it can watch videos, listen to music, play games, read e-books… the experience it brings will be unprecedented.”\nThe first generation of IPAD was presented to the world and opened the curtain of modern tablet computers.The color display and video fluency brought by the LCD panel are unmatched by electronic paper, and there will be more and more tablet terminal devices equipped with LCD screens in the future.Later, the IPAD even added a stylus.\n\n\nThe comfortable layout on the stage shows the simplicity and ease of use of the iPad\nThe industry is worried, can the electronic paper market develop smoothly?\nAt the crossroads, E Ink resolutely chose to stick to his own path and take advantage of the unique features of e-paper.\nMaybe you didn’t notice that e-paper has been used in every corner.\n\n\nSome bus stop signs have been equipped with electronic paper screens, which display bus line information in real time and can be charged by solar energy.\n\n\nThis is the e-paper label in the retail store, which can change the price information at any time, especially for fresh foods with large seasonal changes, which can reduce the waste of a large amount of ingredients.E-paper labels can reduce paper printing, low cost, low power consumption, battery life can be used for more than 5 years, and because of the non-viewing characteristics of e-paper, the shelves from the top to the bottom can be seen at all.It is still clearly visible under strong light.\n\n\nThis is an electronic paper whiteboard from QuirkLogic, a high-contrast 42-inch screen with an ultra-wide viewing angle that displays content as comfortable as real paper, touch-handwriting is very smooth, and has networking capabilities.\n\n\nThe ParceLive e-paper logistics label can display information such as the arrival location and the current status of the goods on the screen, allowing users to track the logistics dynamics at any time, and can update the shipping destination at any time, so that the transport personnel can easily make corresponding changes.\n\n\n12 pieces of 32-inch color electronic paper constitute the National Palace Museum in Taipei, “The Formation of National Treasures — Special Exhibition of Paintings and Calligraphy”, 72 classic national treasures of calligraphy and painting works in turn, electronic paper’s self-illuminating eye protection features allow visitors to observe the national treasure comfortablyEvery detail, low power consumption and low heat characteristics make the environmental temperature of the collection unaffected. Electronic paper has become the first choice for art exhibitions in recent years.\n\n\nElectronic paper is also used in the field of stationery. Supernote provides a new digital note solution with a handwriting experience close to the real pen and paper. It combines natural writing, intelligent processing and multi-end interconnection. The Supernotes are on the way of stationery digitization.\nWhat will happen to the future of electronic paper?We will wait and see.\nReference materials\nHeikenfeld(2011).A critical review of the present and future prospects for electronicpaper.J.Soc.Inf.Display.19(2):129.doi:10.1889/JSID19.2.129.IRex Takes On The Kindle.Forbes.2008–09–23.Retrieved 2008–11–06.Genuth,Iddo.The Future of Electronic Paper.The Future Of Things.Retrieved 2 March 2015.\nComiskey,B.;Albert,J.D.;Yoshizawa,H.;Jacobson,J.(1998).”An electrophoretic ink for all-printed reflective electronic displays”.Nature.394(6690):253–255.doi:10.1038/28349.\nChen Yuwen, Qian Jinwei. The Status Quo and Future Development of Electronic Paper[J]. Modern display, 2009(3):54–57.\nZOL: From carrot to 4 milliseconds, 120 years of LCD development\nJapanese Society BP: What is electronic paper?\nYesky: SONY LIBRIe’s world’s first e-book\nTencent Digital: The history of smart watches has been born in 1971\nE Ink: 🇨🇳.eink.com\n</pre>', '1', '1', '1', 4, '1', '1', '1', '1', '2019-10-28 15:17:30', 'admin', '2019-10-30 14:46:18', 'admin');

